        <body>
             <div type="edition" subtype="ogham" xml:space="preserve" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" resp="#POC"><!--update lang and resp here-->              
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:l-to-r"/><unclear reason="worn">ᚁ</unclear><unclear reason="worn">ᚐ</unclear><unclear reason="worn">ᚁ</unclear>
                </ab> 
            </div>
            <div type="edition" subtype="transliteration" xml:lang="pgl-Ogam" xml:space="preserve" resp="#POC">
                <ab>
                    <lb n="1" style="text-direction:l-to-r"/><unclear reason="worn">B</unclear><unclear reason="worn">A</unclear><unclear reason="worn">B</unclear>
                </ab>
            </div>
            <div type="apparatus">
                <listApp>
                <app n="1">
<note>The direction of reading is dependent on the position in which the stone is held. Regardless of the direction in which the inscription is read, it does not yield and particular sense. One possible reading is:</note>                    
               <rdg>BAB</rdg>
                </app>   
                </listApp>
            </div>
            <div type="translation">
                <p>The text is most likely an example of casual graffiti.</p>
            </div>
            <div type="commentary">
                 <p>It is possible that this object was a gaming piece. If so, the ogham characters of Birsay 4 might offer further evidence for ogham literacy in a recreational context. The use of ogham in a recreational context is also attested in Inchmarnock 2 (S-BUT-003) and Inchmarnock 3 (S-BUT-004).</p>
            </div>
